"1355–1375","1285–Male":"1285–Deceased","1324":"1324","1355":"1355","Abt 1376":"about 1376","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","1330":"1330","1285":"1285","1382":"1382","Drayton, Warwickshire, England":"Drayton, Warwickshire, England","Sefton, Lancashire, England":"Sefton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Drayton, Oxfordshire, England":"Drayton, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Molineux","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Molyneux  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Molyneux","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): occupational name from Old French <i>molineux</i> ‘miller’, a variant of <i>molineur</i>, <i>molinier</i>. See   Mulliner  .","English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from an unidentified French placename.","Irish: adoption for   Mulligan  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Molineux was born in 1324, in Sefton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of John de Molyneux. She married Giles de Arderne. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1382, at the age of 58."},"et":{"1324–1382":"1324–1382","1330–1376":"1330–1376","1355–1375":"1355–1375","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1324":"1324","1355":"1355","Abt 1376":"umbes 1376","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","1330":"1330","1285":"1285","1382":"1382","Drayton, Warwickshire, England":"Drayton, Warwickshire, England","Sefton, Lancashire, England":"Sefton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Drayton, Oxfordshire, England":"Drayton, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1324–1382":"1324–1382","1330–1376":"1330–137